By the end of four short tutorials, you'll have a running Jido agent with typed state, composed actions, and optional LLM reasoning - all inside a standard Elixir project. Each step builds on the last and takes under fifteen minutes.

## The onboarding path

1. **[Installation and setup](/docs/learn/installation)** - add Jido to a project, configure dependencies, and verify everything compiles.
2. **[Build your first agent](/docs/learn/first-agent)** - define an agent with typed state and actions. No LLM required.
3. **[Build your first LLM agent](/docs/learn/first-llm-agent)** - wire up an LLM so your agent can reason about instructions.
4. **[Build your first workflow](/docs/learn/first-workflow)** - compose actions into a multi-step workflow that runs as a single unit.

Start at step 1 and work through in order. Each tutorial ends with a working result you can run in IEx.

## What you'll need

- **Elixir 1.16+** and **OTP 26+** installed ([elixir-lang.org/install](https://elixir-lang.org/install.html))
- Basic comfort with Elixir modules, functions, and Mix
- An LLM API key (OpenAI, Anthropic, or similar) - only needed for step 3

## Where to go after

Once you finish the onboarding path, pick the track that fits what you're building:

- **[Learn](/docs/learn)** - structured training modules that go deeper on agents, sensors, signals, and skills
- **[Concepts](/docs/concepts)** - the mental model behind Jido's architecture
- **[Guides](/docs/guides)** - task-oriented recipes for common patterns

